PROOF POLICY
Use the proof_level from the blueprint data if available. If not specified, default to "soft".
- If "none": remove all proof language except process credibility.
- If "soft": allowed: "Case studies available upon request" and "Outcomes we measure for include..." (no numbers). Replace any instance of "Typical outcomes include..." with "Outcomes we measure for include..."
- If "hard": keep proof only if it exists in the draft AND is explicitly supported by input facts.

STYLE TARGETS (write like a sharp, helpful strategist)
- Replace vague phrases with concrete deliverables.
- Prefer "what you get" over "what we believe."
- Use plain English.
- Avoid inflated adjectives. If a word feels like marketing fog, cut it.

FORMAT CONTROL
Output must be clean Markdown only. Do not mix Markdown and raw HTML in the same draft.
- Use Markdown headings (#, ##, ###), bold (**), italic (*), bullet lists (-), and numbered lists (1.).
- Do NOT insert HTML tags (<div>, <span>, <a>, <style>, etc.) anywhere in the draft.
- CTA blocks must be plain Markdown links: `[Button Text →](#anchor)` — no inline styles, no HTML buttons.

HEADING HIERARCHY RULE
Enforce strict H1 → H2 → H3 nesting. No skipping levels.
- Exactly ONE H1 (#) — the page title. No second H1 anywhere.
- H2 (##) for major sections. Every H2 must be a direct child of H1.
- H3 (###) only inside an H2 section. Never use H3 without a parent H2 above it.
- Do NOT use H4 or deeper. If you need sub-points under H3, use bold text or bullet lists.
- Do NOT use headings for CTA blocks — CTAs are paragraph-level content, not sections.
If the incoming draft violates this hierarchy, fix it during harmonization.

HERO DELIVERABLE REQUIREMENT
The hero section (H1 + subhead area) must name at least one concrete output the reader will receive.
Examples of valid hero deliverables: "a prioritized use-case list," "a phased roadmap," "a pilot plan with KPIs," "a readiness assessment."
Do NOT allow a hero that only contains abstract promises ("practical outcomes," "real results"). If the draft hero is vague, rewrite it to anchor on a specific deliverable.

"WHAT WE WON'T RECOMMEND" SECTION
If the draft includes a "What We Won't Recommend" section, preserve it. These bullets describe restraint, not capability, and do NOT require input facts. Tighten the wording for BT voice but keep each bullet direct and specific.

OUTPUT REQUIREMENTS
- Return clean Markdown only. No HTML tags anywhere.
- Keep the same H1/H2 structure unless you remove redundancy or merge thin sections.
- Ensure there are exactly 2 CTA blocks (top and bottom). If the draft has more, consolidate.

Return ONLY valid JSON with exactly these keys:
- draft (string): the full rewritten draft as a single string in clean Markdown. No HTML tags.

No markdown fences. No extra keys.